    </p>

    <h2>First 30 Minutes: Contain the Damage</h2>
    <p>
      Before anything else, limit how far the water travels. This protects your belongings and
      your home's structure — and it documents the damage for your insurance claim.
    </p>

    <ol class="action-steps">
      <li>
        <div>
          <strong>Contain the water.</strong> Place buckets under active drips. Lay towels on the floor. If you can see a bulging area in your ceiling (a water bubble), carefully poke a small hole in the center to let the water drain in a controlled stream rather than letting it spread across the ceiling and collapse suddenly.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <div>
          <strong>Move valuables and electronics.</strong> Get everything you care about out of the wet zone. Water conducts electricity — if there's any chance it's near a light fixture or outlet, avoid the area and consider cutting power to that circuit.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <div>
          <strong>Document before you clean up.</strong> Take photos and video of the leak, the wet area, and any visible damage. Don't clean anything up yet — your insurer needs evidence of the initial damage, not just the aftermath.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <div>
          <strong>Call a licensed roofing contractor.</strong> Not a handyman — a licensed roofer who handles emergency calls. They can tarp the roof the same day if needed to stop the bleeding, and they'll document the damage in a way that supports your insurance claim.
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <div>
          <strong>Call your insurer.</strong> After you've got a contractor in the loop, report the claim. Most Utah policies require "prompt notice" of damage — which in practice means within a few days of the event.
        </div>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <div class="callout urgent">
      <p><strong>Do NOT get on the roof yourself</strong> during or immediately after rain. Wet roofing surfaces are extremely slippery. Let a licensed contractor handle the assessment and any emergency tarping.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>What Causes Emergency Roof Leaks in Sandy, UT</h2>

    <p>
      Understanding the cause matters because it affects both the repair approach and the insurance
      coverage. The most common emergency leak causes in Salt Lake County:
    </p>

    <h3>Storm Damage</h3>
    <p>
      Wind-driven rain, hail impacts, and falling branches are the most common trigger for sudden
      leaks. Utah's spring and summer storm season (typically April through August) produces
      fast-moving cells that can strip shingles, crack flashing, or deposit debris that dams water
      on flat sections of the roof. Storm-caused leaks are typically covered by homeowners insurance.
    </p>

    <h3>Ice Dams</h3>
    <p>
      In winter, heat escaping through your attic melts snow on the upper part of your roof. That
      water runs down and refreezes at the eaves, forming an ice dam. Water backs up behind the dam
      and gets under shingles — often leaking into the top-floor ceiling or walls. Ice dams are
      common in Sandy, Draper, and Cottonwood Heights homes with insufficient attic insulation.
    </p>

    <h3>Failed Flashing</h3>
    <p>
      Flashing — the metal strips that seal joints around chimneys, skylights, vents, and valleys —
      is often the actual leak point even when people blame the shingles. Flashing can pull away,
      corrode, or be improperly installed, creating entry points that aren't visible unless you're
      on the roof looking closely. Flashing failures are often the result of age or improper
      installation rather than storm damage, which affects insurance coverage.
    </p>

    <h3>Cracked or Missing Shingles</h3>
    <p>
      Shingles that have aged, blistered, or been physically damaged by debris create open
      waterproofing gaps. A single missing shingle in a rain event can introduce enough water
      to damage insulation and drywall within hours.
    </p>

    <h2>What Emergency Roof Repair Looks Like</h2>

    <p>
      When a licensed contractor responds to an emergency call, here's what typically happens:
    </p>

    <p>
      First, they assess the immediate situation — finding the entry point as quickly as possible.
      If the repair can be done the same day and the weather allows, they'll do it. If rain is
      ongoing, or if the repair scope requires scheduling materials or crew, they'll install a
      waterproof tarp over the affected section. A properly installed emergency tarp can hold
      through multiple storm events while the permanent repair is arranged.
    </p>

    <p>
      The contractor will also document the damage — photos, measurements, written notes — which
      is essential if you're filing an insurance claim. A contractor who does insurance work
      regularly knows exactly what an adjuster needs to see.
    </p>

    <h2>Emergency Roof Repair Cost in Sandy, UT (2026)</h2>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Emergency tarp installation:</strong> $300 – $800 (depends on roof pitch and size)</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency patching (minor):</strong> $400 – $1,200</li>
      <li><strong>Flashing repair:</strong> $350 – $900</li>
      <li><strong>Shingle replacement (small section):</strong> $400 – $1,000</li>
      <li><strong>After-hours / weekend response premium:</strong> 15–30% above standard rate</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      If the leak is storm-related and covered by insurance, your out-of-pocket is typically your
      deductible ($1,000–$2,500). Emergency repairs done before the full claim is settled can
      be included in the claim if properly documented.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <p><strong>Keep your receipts.</strong> Any emergency mitigation costs — tarps, buckets, water extraction — are typically reimbursable under the dwelling coverage or loss mitigation provisions of your homeowners policy. Document everything.</p>
    </div>

